title: For Sale:  58 cal. Musket & horn
postcontent: 58 caliber smooth bore cap & ball musket.  I reconditioned it, the rear sight I put on was fabricated out of an original elk horn sight that I cut down, I plumb blued the barrel, I made the ram-rod, I put new front stock and barrel band on, I put a new nipple where the cap goes on the barrel and new flash pan, new ram-rod spring on the stock, new strap, repaired stock by the barrel strap by the hammer with new piece of wood.  Originally someone cut the front stock off where the middle copper barrel band is and they made a shotgun out of it.  I bought a new walnut Springfield stock and cut it to fit and installed it to this rifle.  The wood matches perfectly.  I got most of what I needed to recondition this rifle from Dixie Gun Works and I spent over $300.   and over two weeks of work.   The gun was found on my uncles property in an old log cabin that was torn down over 45 years ago on a farm in Licking County, I researched it and couldn't find out where the gun was made so I took it to a gun show and an old man told me it was made in Belgium after looking at the markings.  The reason I reconditioned this rifle is because of the lock mechanism, it's the strongest and best I've ever seen on a Muzzle Loader.  It has an anchor on the side of the lock with other markings.  I can email you more pictures.  There's a lot of brass and copper components on this rifle that are all original.  I also reconditioned the powder horn that's seen in the picture, I made a plug for the spout and put a new leather strap on it.  It's an early powder horn that my brother bought at an auction.  This gun would look good over a fire place or on the wall behind a wood burner, it's an early piece of american history and one only knows, it may have served in our american civil war.  It's amazing that the barrel isn't pitted or dark.My price is firm.
